which stemmed from a flawed deregulation plan that has hit the state with a series of rolling blackouts
under the agreement
calpine will continue to receive its contractual capacity payments
but it has also set up a fixed rate contract for the next five years of about 0.0 cents per kilowatt-hour
the contracts are known as qualifying facility contracts because calpine's power plants are qualifying facilities
these types of facilities represent more than 0 percent of the state's power supply and sell power generated from renewable energy sources to the regulated utilities
calpine is the first power company to modify its qf contract with pg&e to ensure that northern california consumers will continue to benefit from these affordable and reliable energy resources
calpine senior vice president james macias said in a statement
